  "texts": [
    "As later commentators have urged, it is implausible that each action for which an agent is responsible is caused by a discrete belief-desire pairing (even if one is a 'realist' about these putative mental entities) (see, e.g., Velleman, 1992; Heuer, 2004).",
    "But, at least for current purposes, what's essential to the standard story is not in the details of which psychological states play the role of Davidson's primary reasons but in the claim that some psychological state attributed to the agent must play this pivotal role.",
    "Reasons, for Davidson, are psychological states that both cause and rationalise corresponding actions; and actions are the interface between an agent's reasons and the changes she makes to the world in responding to them.",
    "An important upshot of this model and the picture of causation it is embedded in is the notion of the 'basic action' (Amaya, 2017).",
    "9 Basic actions are where the means-7 Here Davidson is quoting David Hume (1740)."
  ],
